        "timestamp": "2018-11-27 15:52:59.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nBrendan, \n\nTwo points:\n1. I think if we return result set then we are again falling into this trap of expecting the client to understand a CQL/SQL like construct. I think it is better to just return the list of lock references. So in your select query just return the column \"lockReference\" in string form. \n2. This query by definition requires you to iterate through the entire table. While this function maybe useful and we should keep it, I think we should add another function called \"howManyWaiting\" that simply returns the number of items in the queue. That can use the select count(*) query. This will ensure the code does not iterate through the lock queue.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
